Specifically , $(C_{21^\prime},C_{22^\prime},C_{23^\prime})=(\sqrt{1/30},\sqrt{1/6},\sqrt{7/15})$ .
For example , the Hamiltonian for a weak probe field with frequency $\omega^\prime$ is then ,
\begin{eqnarray}
\hat{H}^\prime = \frac{\hbar\Omega^\prime}{2}\left(\hat{\Sigma}e^{i\omega^\prime t} + \hat{\Sigma}^\dagger e^{-i\omega^\prime t}\right)\quad,
\label{eq:Hprime}
\end{eqnarray}
where $\hat{\Sigma} = \sum_{F^\prime}C_{2F^\prime}|2\rangle\langle F^\prime|$ is the weighted sum of atomic lowering operators .
Working in the interaction picture and rotating wave approximation , the absorbed power is proportional to ,
\begin{eqnarray}\nonumber
\mathcal{P} &=& \left\langle\partial_t\hat{H}^\prime(t)\right\rangle \\
&=& \hbar\omega^\prime\left(\frac{\Omega^{\prime}}{2}\right)^{\!\!2}\int_{-\infty}^\infty d\tau\left\langle [\hat{\Sigma}(\tau), \hat{\Sigma}^\dagger(0)]\right\rangle e^{i\omega^\prime\tau}\;.
\label{eq:spectrum}
\end{eqnarray}
The average $\langle\cdot\rangle$ is obtained from the master equation for the density operator $\rho$ , with respect to the pump Hamiltonian $\hat{H}_0$ in the absence of the probe ( $\hat{H}_0$ has the same form as $\hat{H}^\prime$ , but with Rabi and optical frequencies associated with the pump light ) ,
