\begin{abstract}
We study optical gain in a gas of cold $^{39}$ K atoms .
The gain is observed during operation of a conventional magneto-optical trap without the need for additional fields .
Measurements of transmission spectra from a weak probe show that the gain is due to stimulated Raman scattering between hyperfine ground states .
The experimental results are reproduced by a simplified six - level model , which also helps explain why such gain is not observed in similar experiments with rubidium or cesium .
\end{abstract}

