We choose an electric potential $V = 1/{| z |}$ , which we expand in series around $z_0 > 0$ , with $z - z_0 = x - y$ .
The expression of the potential energy for a system of two levitated ions can be cast into :

\begin{equation}
\label{ham2} H = \frac 12 \left( {p_\rho^2} + {p_z^2} \right) + U\left( \rho, z \right) \ ,
\end{equation}
where
\begin{equation}
\label{ham3} U\left( \rho, z\right) = \frac 12 \left( \rho^2 + \lambda^2 z^2 \right) + \frac{\nu^2}{2 \rho^2} + \frac 1r \ ,
\end{equation}
and $r = \sqrt{\rho^2 + z^2} \ , \; \lambda = \mu_z/\mu_x \ , \; \mu_z = \sqrt{2\left( q^2 - a\right) }$ .
$\nu $ is the scaled axial ( $z$ ) component of the angular momentum $L_z$ , and it represents a constant of motion , while $\mu_z$ represents the second secular frequency \cite{Blu89} .
Both $\lambda$ and $\nu$ are positive control parameters .
For arbitrary $\nu $ and $\lambda = 1/2, 1, 2$ , eq. ( \ref{ham3} ) is integrable and even separable , except the case when $\lambda = 1/2$ and $ \left| \nu \right| > 0$ $\left( \nu \neq 0 \right) $ , as stated in \cite{Moore93} .
